Our device reads directory entries off a painfully slow SPI flash, so we front it with a small cache keyed by record id. The target build has NO heap -- every byte of cache storage is an array the board support code hands over at init -- so this must be the classic embedded pattern: entries that carry their own links (hash chain + recency list woven through the entry structs themselves), a freelist over the unused slots, and zero allocation ever. lru.h and lru.c, C17, stdint.h/stddef.h only.

The header must define exactly this layout and API (the BSP allocates lru_entry arrays, so the struct is part of the ABI):

    #define LRU_BUCKETS 32

    typedef struct lru_entry {
        uint32_t key;
        uint32_t value;
        struct lru_entry *hnext;        /* hash-chain link */
        struct lru_entry *prev, *next;  /* recency-list links */
    } lru_entry;

    typedef struct {
        lru_entry *slots;       /* caller storage: cap entries */
        size_t     cap;
        size_t     len;
        lru_entry *mru, *lru;   /* recency list ends */
        lru_entry *free_head;   /* unused slots, chained via hnext */
        lru_entry *buckets[LRU_BUCKETS];
        uint32_t   hits, misses, evictions;
    } lru_cache;

    int      lru_init(lru_cache *c, lru_entry *slots, size_t cap);
    int      lru_get(lru_cache *c, uint32_t key, uint32_t *value_out);
    void     lru_put(lru_cache *c, uint32_t key, uint32_t value);
    int      lru_contains(const lru_cache *c, uint32_t key);
    size_t   lru_len(const lru_cache *c);
    uint32_t lru_hits(const lru_cache *c);
    uint32_t lru_misses(const lru_cache *c);
    uint32_t lru_evictions(const lru_cache *c);
    size_t   lru_keys_mru(const lru_cache *c, uint32_t *out, size_t max);

Semantics:

- lru_init: 0 on success, -1 if slots is NULL or cap is 0. Threads all cap slots onto the freelist, empties the buckets, zeroes len and the counters. Two caches over different arrays must not interfere (no globals, no statics).
- Bucket index is key % LRU_BUCKETS. Lookups walk one chain; the recency list is doubly linked so promotion and eviction are O(1) pointer surgery. Record ids on flash are sequential multiples, so long same-bucket chains are normal life, not a corner case.
- lru_get: hit -> write the value through value_out (a NULL value_out just promotes), move the entry to MRU, count a hit, return 1. Miss -> count a miss, return 0.
- lru_put with a known key updates the value and promotes -- len unchanged, nothing evicted. With a new key: if the cache is full, unlink the LRU entry first (from its hash chain AND the recency list), count an eviction, and recycle that very slot for the new entry; then insert as MRU. After warmup the cache runs forever on the same cap slots.
- lru_contains reports presence without promoting and without touching any counter.
- lru_keys_mru writes up to max keys most-recent-first and returns how many it wrote.
- Counters only ever increase; len never exceeds cap.

Getting the two unlink paths right in the same struct is the whole job; the tests hammer same-bucket collisions and a 100-put run over 4 slots. `make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_lru.c are fixed.
